deepest questions. It shows how the problem of consciousness merges with questions that obsess us all--how life should be lived and the fear of death. Resting firmly on neuroscience and evolutionary theory, and drawing a wealth of insights from philosophy and literature, Soul Dust is an uncompromising yet life-affirming work--one that never loses sight of the majesty and wonder of consciousness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aConsciousness. 0aPHILOSOPHYvMind &ampxBody. 0aPSYCHOLOGYvGeneral. 0aPSYCHOLOGYvPersonality. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Mind & Body.2bisacsh  aAldous Huxley.  aAnalogy.  aAnthony Marcel.  aAnthropologist.  aBehavior.  aBuddhism.  aCheating death.  aChildlessness.  aChimpanzee.  aChristopher Isherwood.  aConcept.  aConsciousness.  aCulture.  aDaniel Dennett.  aDeath anxiety (psychology).  aDecision-making.  aDelay differential equation.  aDevelopmental psychology.  aDouglas Hofstadter.  aDualism (philosophy of mind).  aDylan Evans.  aEmergence.  aEnthusiasm.  aExistence.  aExplanation.  aFaber and Faber.  aFeeling.  aGeorge Santayana.  aGod.  aHard problem of consciousness.  aHeat death of the universe.  aHuman.  aIllustration.  aIncorruptibility.  aIndication (medicine).  aIndividualism.  aIndividuation.  aIneffability.  aInstance (computer science).  aInstant.  aIntentionality.  aJohansson.  aLecture.  aLiterary agent.  aLudwig Wittgenstein.  aMatt Ridley.  aMental representation.  aMescaline.  aMidwife.  aMortality salience.  aNarrative.  aNiche construction.  aPenguin Books.  aPerception.  aPersonhood.  aPessimism.  aPhenomenon.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophical zombie.  aPhilosophy.  aPity.  aPrecognition.  aPrinciple.  aProbability.  aPsychology.  aQualia.  aReali